An embodiment of a gas sensor and associated gas cell according to an embodiment at present described and having features significant of the present invention will now be described in more detail with reference to the accompanying drawings, in which


FIG. 1 is a greatly simplified illustration of a gas sensor having a gas cell in accordance with the invention and the electronics necessary for evaluating the frequency dependency of the light intensity within a spectral analytical or analyzing arrangement;


FIG. 2 is a first perspective view of the outer configuration of the gas cell;


FIG. 3 is a second perspective view of the gas cell shown in FIG. 2;


FIG. 4 is intended to illustrate the shape of a first concave wall-part or mirror surface of a chosen cavity;


FIG. 5 is intended to illustrate the shapes of second and third concave wall-parts or mirror surfaces of the chosen cavity that oppose said first mirror surface;


FIG. 6 is a view from above taken through a central plane (the x-z plane) geometry showing three opposing mirror surfaces included in a gas cell according to FIGS. 2 and 3;


FIG. 7 is a sectional view similar to FIG. 6 with a central plane but with slightly enlarged opposing cavity-forming wall-parts which form mirror surfaces in the gas cell, and shows the orientation of associated ellipse centra;


FIG. 8 illustrates in a central plane, by way of simplification, a first chosen beam path (for the central beam) representative of an optical analysis path from a light source to a first outlet opening, and shows a centrally placed light source that generates a divergent light bundle and enables (as shown in a broken beam path) two mutually separate optical analysis paths to be created within one and the same cavity and from one and the same light source;


FIG. 9 illustrates a beam path (for the central beam) at a laterally positioned light source and illuminating initially a second mirror part, forming an optical analysis path that has five reflection points;


FIG. 10 illustrates a beam path (for the central beam) at a laterally positioned light source similar to that of FIG. 9 but illuminating initially a third mirror part that provides a shorter optical analysis path that includes three reflection points; and


FIG. 11 is a sectional view of the cavity in the gas cell taken on the line XI--XI in FIG. 8.
